const QUESTIONS_CRISC_C1 = [
  { id:40101, domain:1, level:2, question:"Which document defines the high-level intentions and direction of management regarding information risk?", options:["A security policy that states management's intent and direction on risk","A technical baseline that lists required server hardening configuration items","A network diagram that maps every device and connection in the environment","An incident log that records each event handled by the operations team"], correct:0, explanation:"A policy expresses management intent and direction. A hardening baseline is a standard, a network diagram is documentation, and an incident log is an operational record, none of which state intent." },
  { id:40102, domain:1, level:1, question:"What BEST describes the purpose of an enterprise risk management (ERM) framework within governance?", options:["To replace the need for any internal audit activity across the organization by design","To provide a consistent structure for identifying, assessing, and responding to risk","To guarantee that no risk event will ever materially affect the enterprise","To document only the technical controls deployed on production systems"], correct:1, explanation:"An ERM framework gives a consistent structure for managing risk enterprise-wide. It does not replace audit, cannot guarantee zero loss, and is far broader than technical controls alone." },
  { id:40103, domain:1, level:1, question:"In the three lines of defense model, which group OWNS and manages risk as part of daily operations?", options:["Internal audit, which provides independent assurance over the control environment","The risk management function that designs frameworks and monitors exposure","Operational management that owns processes and the risks within them daily","External regulators who review compliance with mandated legal requirements"], correct:2, explanation:"The first line is operational management that owns and manages risk. Internal audit is the third line, risk management is the second line, and regulators are external to the model." },
  { id:40104, domain:1, level:2, question:"What does 'risk appetite' represent for an organization?", options:["The maximum loss the organization could theoretically suffer in any scenario","A list of all technical vulnerabilities currently present in the environment","The exact probability that a specific threat event will occur next year","The amount and type of risk an organization is willing to pursue or accept"], correct:3, explanation:"Risk appetite is the amount of risk an entity is willing to pursue or accept. Maximum loss relates to capacity, vulnerabilities are technical findings, and probability is a likelihood estimate." },
  { id:40105, domain:1, level:3, question:"How does 'risk tolerance' differ from 'risk appetite' in risk governance?", options:["Tolerance is the acceptable variation around objectives, appetite is broad willingness","Tolerance is always larger than appetite and applies only to financial exposure by design","Tolerance applies to the board while appetite applies only to operational staff","Tolerance and appetite are identical terms used interchangeably in all contexts"], correct:0, explanation:"Tolerance is the acceptable variation around specific objectives, while appetite is the broad level of willingness. They are not identical, not role-specific in that way, and tolerance is not always larger." },
  { id:40106, domain:1, level:3, question:"A board wants IT risk decisions aligned to strategy. Which action MOST directly achieves this alignment?", options:["Increasing the frequency of vulnerability scans across all production servers","Linking IT risk scenarios to specific enterprise objectives and value drivers","Purchasing additional cyber insurance to transfer more residual exposure","Mandating that every employee complete annual security awareness training"], correct:1, explanation:"Mapping IT risk to enterprise objectives creates strategic alignment. Scanning, insurance, and training are useful operational measures but do not by themselves align risk decisions to strategy." },
  { id:40107, domain:1, level:3, question:"Who is PRIMARILY accountable for accepting residual risk on a specific business process?", options:["The information security analyst who configured the supporting technical controls","The internal audit manager who reviews the effectiveness of those controls","The business risk owner who owns the process and its outcomes and exposure","The external consultant engaged to perform the original risk assessment work"], correct:2, explanation:"The risk owner accepts residual risk for their process. Analysts implement controls, audit provides assurance, and consultants advise; none of these accept the risk on the owner's behalf." },
  { id:40108, domain:1, level:1, question:"What is the role of a 'control owner' in a governance structure?", options:["To formally accept residual risk remaining after the control has been applied","To set the overall enterprise risk appetite for the board of directors","To perform independent assurance reviews of the entire control environment","To ensure an assigned control is designed, operating, and maintained"], correct:3, explanation:"A control owner ensures their control works effectively. Accepting residual risk is the risk owner's role, setting appetite is the board's, and independent assurance is audit's role." },
  { id:40109, domain:1, level:2, question:"Why is organizational culture important when establishing a risk governance program?", options:["Culture shapes how people perceive, report, and respond to risk day to day","Culture determines the exact monetary value of every identified risk scenario","Culture removes the requirement to document any formal policies or standards","Culture is only relevant to marketing functions and not to risk management"], correct:0, explanation:"Culture drives risk perception and behavior across the enterprise. It does not set monetary values, does not remove policy needs, and is relevant well beyond marketing." },
  { id:40110, domain:1, level:3, question:"An enterprise's risk appetite statement conflicts with an approved strategic initiative. What should be done FIRST?", options:["Immediately cancel the strategic initiative to stay within the stated appetite","Escalate the conflict to the board or risk committee for resolution and direction","Quietly raise the appetite limits so the initiative can proceed without review","Proceed with the initiative and document the conflict only in next year's report by design"], correct:1, explanation:"A conflict between appetite and strategy must be escalated for governance resolution. Cancelling, quietly raising limits, or ignoring it all bypass proper governance decision-making." },
  { id:40111, domain:1, level:3, question:"What is the PRIMARY purpose of risk governance within an enterprise?", options:["To eliminate all sources of uncertainty from the organization's operations","To assign blame to individuals whenever a risk event eventually materializes","To direct and oversee how risk is managed in support of business objectives","To centralize all technical decision-making within the IT department alone"], correct:2, explanation:"Risk governance directs and oversees risk management toward objectives. It cannot eliminate uncertainty, is not about blame, and is not about centralizing technical decisions in IT." },
  { id:40112, domain:1, level:1, question:"Which term describes the maximum amount of risk an organization is able to absorb?", options:["Risk appetite, the subjective amount of risk leadership prefers to accept by design","Risk tolerance, the allowable variation around a particular set objective","Risk velocity, the speed at which a risk event progresses to its impact","Risk capacity, the objective limit of risk the enterprise can actually bear"], correct:3, explanation:"Risk capacity is the objective maximum an enterprise can absorb. Appetite is willingness, tolerance is variation around objectives, and velocity describes speed of impact." },
  { id:40113, domain:1, level:2, question:"How should policies, standards, and procedures relate to each other in a governance hierarchy?", options:["Policies set intent, standards set mandatory rules, procedures give step detail","Procedures set intent, standards are optional, and policies describe each step","Standards set intent while policies and procedures are entirely interchangeable","All three are equivalent documents that may be used in any order required"], correct:0, explanation:"Policies state intent, standards mandate rules, and procedures provide steps. The other options invert or flatten this hierarchy, which would break governance consistency." },
  { id:40114, domain:1, level:2, question:"A new regulation imposes data localization rules. Which governance activity addresses this MOST appropriately?", options:["Asking developers to immediately rewrite the application without any analysis","Updating policies and the compliance register to reflect the new legal obligation","Transferring the entire compliance risk to a third-party cloud hosting provider by design","Documenting the regulation in a personal note kept by the compliance officer"], correct:1, explanation:"Updating policies and the compliance register formalizes the obligation in governance. Rushed rewrites, blanket transfer, and personal notes fail to embed the requirement properly." },
  { id:40115, domain:1, level:3, question:"What is the MAIN benefit of clearly defined risk roles and responsibilities?", options:["Risk events become impossible because every role is documented in writing","The cost of all controls is automatically reduced across the organization","Accountability is established so risk decisions are made by the right people","Internal audit no longer needs to review any risk-related activities in any way at any time"], correct:2, explanation:"Clear roles establish accountability for decisions. They do not make risk events impossible, do not automatically cut control costs, and do not remove the need for audit." },
  { id:40116, domain:1, level:3, question:"What is 'risk culture' within an organization?", options:["A documented catalog listing every technical vulnerability found by scanners","The legal contract that transfers liability to an external insurance provider","A fixed numerical score assigned to each department by the audit committee","The shared values and behaviors that influence how risk is handled"], correct:3, explanation:"Risk culture is the shared values and behaviors around risk. It is not a vulnerability catalog, an insurance contract, or a fixed numerical score." },
  { id:40117, domain:1, level:1, question:"Why should the board of directors be involved in setting risk appetite?", options:["The board holds ultimate accountability for the enterprise's strategic direction","The board personally configures the technical security controls each quarter by design","The board performs the detailed risk assessments for every business unit","The board reviews and approves each individual change request to systems"], correct:0, explanation:"The board is ultimately accountable for strategy, so it owns appetite. It does not configure controls, perform detailed assessments, or approve individual changes." },
  { id:40118, domain:1, level:2, question:"Management wants to demonstrate that IT risk supports business value. Which metric is MOST relevant?", options:["The total number of firewall rules currently active across the entire network by design","The degree to which IT risk responses enable achievement of business objectives","The count of patches applied to endpoints during the previous calendar month","The raw volume of log entries collected by the monitoring platform each day"], correct:1, explanation:"Linking risk responses to business objective achievement shows value. Firewall counts, patch counts, and log volumes are activity metrics that do not demonstrate business value." },
  { id:40119, domain:1, level:3, question:"What distinguishes a 'standard' from a 'guideline' in policy documentation?", options:["A standard is optional advice, while a guideline must always be strictly followed","A standard applies only to executives, while a guideline applies only to staff","A standard is mandatory and enforceable, a guideline is recommended best practice","A standard and a guideline are identical and may be used interchangeably always"], correct:2, explanation:"Standards are mandatory while guidelines are recommendations. The other choices reverse the relationship, restrict them by role incorrectly, or wrongly call them identical." },
  { id:40120, domain:1, level:2, question:"Which of the following BEST reflects integrating risk management with corporate governance?", options:["Running an isolated risk team that reports to no one within the enterprise","Treating risk only as a compliance checkbox completed once each fiscal year","Limiting all risk discussion exclusively to the information technology group by design","Embedding risk considerations into strategic planning and key decision processes"], correct:3, explanation:"Integration means embedding risk into strategy and decisions. An isolated team, an annual checkbox, or IT-only scope all represent poor integration with governance." },
  { id:40121, domain:1, level:2, question:"In the three lines of defense model, what is the role of internal audit?", options:["To provide independent and objective assurance over governance and controls","To own and manage operational risks as part of daily business activities","To design the risk framework and continuously monitor enterprise exposure by design","To set the organization's overall risk appetite on behalf of the board"], correct:0, explanation:"Internal audit is the third line providing independent assurance. Owning risk is the first line, framework design is the second line, and setting appetite is the board's role." },
  { id:40122, domain:1, level:3, question:"A company outsources a critical process to a vendor. Where does accountability for the associated risk reside?", options:["Entirely with the vendor, because the vendor now performs all of the work","With the company, since accountability for outsourced risk cannot be delegated away","With the regulator that oversees the industry sector the company operates in by design","With the insurance provider that issued the company's cyber liability policy"], correct:1, explanation:"Accountability for outsourced risk stays with the organization even when work is delegated. The vendor, regulator, and insurer do not assume the company's accountability." },
  { id:40123, domain:1, level:3, question:"What is the purpose of a risk committee within an enterprise governance structure?", options:["To personally remediate every technical vulnerability identified by scanning tools","To replace the chief executive in making all day-to-day operational decisions","To oversee risk management activities and advise the board on key exposures","To perform penetration testing against the organization's production systems"], correct:2, explanation:"A risk committee oversees risk activities and advises the board. It does not remediate vulnerabilities, replace the CEO, or conduct penetration testing itself." },
  { id:40124, domain:1, level:2, question:"Why are professional ethics important for risk management practitioners?", options:["They guarantee that every risk assessment will produce a favorable outcome by design","They eliminate the need to follow any organizational policies or standards","They apply only when a practitioner is interacting with external auditors","They guide objective, honest conduct that preserves trust in risk reporting"], correct:3, explanation:"Ethics ensure objective, honest conduct that sustains trust. They do not guarantee favorable outcomes, replace policies, or apply only with external auditors." },
  { id:40125, domain:1, level:2, question:"What is an 'organizational asset' in the context of risk governance?", options:["Anything of value to the enterprise, including data, systems, people, and reputation","Only the physical computer hardware located inside the primary data center by design","Strictly the financial cash reserves held in the corporate bank accounts","Exclusively the software licenses purchased during the current fiscal year"], correct:0, explanation:"An asset is anything of value, including data, systems, people, and reputation. The other options are far too narrow, limiting assets to hardware, cash, or licenses." },
  { id:40126, domain:1, level:3, question:"Risk reporting to the board is consistently too technical. What governance improvement is MOST effective?", options:["Adding more raw technical metrics so the board sees the full level of detail","Translating technical risk into business impact terms the board can act upon","Reducing reporting frequency so the board reviews risk only once each year","Delegating all board risk reporting to the network operations team instead"], correct:1, explanation:"Reporting risk in business impact terms enables board action. Adding technical detail worsens it, less frequent reporting reduces oversight, and delegating to operations is inappropriate." },
  { id:40127, domain:1, level:2, question:"How does risk governance support compliance with legal and regulatory requirements?", options:["By guaranteeing the organization will never be subject to any regulatory fines","By transferring all compliance responsibility to the external legal counsel firm","By establishing accountability and processes that ensure obligations are met","By treating compliance as wholly separate from the enterprise risk program"], correct:2, explanation:"Governance establishes accountability and processes to meet obligations. It cannot guarantee no fines, cannot transfer all responsibility externally, and should integrate compliance, not separate it." },
  { id:40128, domain:1, level:1, question:"What is the relationship between IT risk and business risk?", options:["IT risk is entirely separate and has no bearing on business risk outcomes","Business risk is a narrow subset of the broader IT risk universe overall","IT risk only matters to the technology team and never reaches the business by design","IT risk is a component of business risk and must be managed in that context"], correct:3, explanation:"IT risk is a subset of business risk and managed in that context. It is not separate, business risk is not a subset of IT risk, and IT risk does affect the business." },
  { id:40129, domain:1, level:2, question:"Which body typically holds ultimate responsibility for enterprise risk oversight?", options:["The board of directors, which provides governance and ultimate risk oversight","The IT help desk, which resolves incidents reported by end users each day","The procurement department, which negotiates contracts with external suppliers","The marketing team, which manages the enterprise's external brand presence"], correct:0, explanation:"The board holds ultimate risk oversight responsibility. The help desk, procurement, and marketing perform operational functions but do not provide enterprise risk oversight." },
  { id:40130, domain:1, level:1, question:"An organization's risk appetite is undocumented, causing inconsistent decisions. What should be recommended FIRST?", options:["Hiring additional security analysts to handle the volume of inconsistent choices","Developing and formally approving a risk appetite statement to guide decisions","Purchasing a new governance software tool before defining any appetite at all","Allowing each department to set its own independent appetite without alignment"], correct:1, explanation:"A formally approved appetite statement enables consistent decisions. More analysts, new tools first, or fragmented departmental appetites do not address the root governance gap." },
  { id:40131, domain:1, level:1, question:"What is the PRIMARY reason to align risk management with organizational strategy?", options:["To make the risk register the single most detailed document in the company","To shift accountability for strategy away from executives and onto the risk team","To ensure risk decisions support the achievement of enterprise objectives","To guarantee that audit findings will never be raised against the organization"], correct:2, explanation:"Aligning risk with strategy ensures decisions support objectives. It is not about document size, shifting strategy accountability, or eliminating audit findings." },
  { id:40132, domain:1, level:3, question:"Which factor MOST influences how much risk an organization is willing to accept?", options:["The personal preference of a single technician on the operations team","The number of servers currently deployed in the production environment","The brand of antivirus software installed on corporate endpoint devices","The enterprise's strategic objectives and the value it seeks to create"], correct:3, explanation:"Strategic objectives and value creation shape acceptable risk. A technician's preference, server counts, and antivirus brand do not drive enterprise risk appetite." },
  { id:40133, domain:1, level:3, question:"What does 'governance' primarily ensure for an organization?", options:["That direction is set, decisions are overseen, and objectives are pursued","That every employee performs identical tasks regardless of their assigned role","That all technical systems run without ever experiencing any downtime at all","That the organization avoids ever entering into contracts with third parties"], correct:0, explanation:"Governance ensures direction-setting and oversight toward objectives. It does not make all roles identical, guarantee zero downtime, or prohibit third-party contracts." },
  { id:40134, domain:1, level:2, question:"A risk practitioner discovers leadership is hiding a known risk from the board. What is the ethical action?", options:["Stay silent to protect the relationship with the leadership team involved by design","Report the concern through appropriate channels to ensure transparent disclosure","Quietly remove the risk from the register so no record of it remains","Wait until next year's report and hope the situation resolves on its own"], correct:1, explanation:"Ethics require transparent disclosure through proper channels. Staying silent, deleting the record, or waiting all violate professional integrity and obstruct governance." },
  { id:40135, domain:1, level:2, question:"How does a defined organizational structure support risk governance?", options:["It guarantees that no employee will ever make an error in risk judgment","It removes the need for any policies because structure replaces documentation","It clarifies reporting lines and accountability for managing risk effectively","It ensures that the IT department controls all enterprise risk decisions alone"], correct:2, explanation:"Structure clarifies reporting and accountability. It does not eliminate human error, replace policies, or give IT sole control over enterprise risk decisions." },
  { id:40136, domain:1, level:2, question:"What is the purpose of embedding risk awareness into the organizational culture?", options:["To ensure only the risk department ever thinks about risk in the company","To replace all formal controls with reliance on individual employee judgment","To reduce the board's involvement in oversight of the risk environment","To encourage employees to identify, report, and respond to risk proactively"], correct:3, explanation:"Embedding awareness encourages proactive risk behavior across staff. It is not about confining risk to one department, removing controls, or reducing board oversight." },
  { id:40137, domain:1, level:3, question:"Which statement BEST describes 'risk owner' accountability?", options:["The risk owner is accountable for managing and responding to an assigned risk","The risk owner only records risks and never decides on any response action","The risk owner is responsible solely for the technical configuration of tools","The risk owner provides independent assurance over the control environment"], correct:0, explanation:"A risk owner is accountable for managing and responding to their risk. They do more than record, are not limited to tool configuration, and do not provide independent assurance." },
  { id:40138, domain:1, level:3, question:"Two business units interpret the same policy differently, causing inconsistent risk responses. What is the BEST fix?", options:["Letting each unit continue with its own interpretation to preserve autonomy","Clarifying the policy and issuing supporting standards to ensure consistency","Escalating every individual risk decision to the board for a final ruling","Removing the policy entirely so there is nothing left to misinterpret at all"], correct:1, explanation:"Clarifying the policy and adding standards drives consistency. Allowing divergent interpretations, escalating every decision, or deleting the policy all fail to resolve the inconsistency." },
  { id:40139, domain:1, level:2, question:"Why should risk appetite be reviewed periodically?", options:["Because the risk register must be reset to empty at the start of each year","Because regulators require the appetite figure to increase every reporting cycle","Because business strategy, environment, and objectives change over time","Because reviewing it removes the need to perform any risk assessments at all"], correct:2, explanation:"Appetite is reviewed because strategy and environment evolve. The register is not reset annually, regulators do not mandate increases, and review does not replace assessments." },
  { id:40140, domain:1, level:2, question:"What is a key characteristic of an effective risk governance framework?", options:["It focuses exclusively on technical controls while ignoring business context by design","It is created once and never updated regardless of organizational change","It is understood only by the risk team and kept hidden from the business","It clearly assigns roles, responsibilities, and accountability for risk decisions"], correct:3, explanation:"An effective framework assigns roles and accountability clearly. Ignoring business context, never updating, or hiding it from the business all undermine effectiveness." },
  { id:40141, domain:1, level:3, question:"What is the function of a 'policy' in risk governance?", options:["To communicate management's intent and set the direction for managing risk","To list the exact technical steps required to configure a single firewall by design","To record the outcome of each individual incident handled by operations","To assign a numeric risk score to every asset owned by the enterprise"], correct:0, explanation:"A policy communicates intent and direction. Exact steps are procedures, incident outcomes are records, and numeric scoring is part of assessment, not policy." },
  { id:40142, domain:1, level:1, question:"Leadership wants risk culture to improve. Which approach is MOST likely to succeed?", options:["Issuing a single email announcement and assuming culture will change overnight by design","Leaders visibly modeling risk-aware behavior and rewarding transparent reporting","Punishing every employee who reports a risk to discourage bad news entirely","Restricting all risk discussion to an annual offsite meeting for executives"], correct:1, explanation:"Visible leadership modeling and rewarding transparency shift culture. A single email, punishing reporters, or restricting discussion all undermine a healthy risk culture." },
  { id:40143, domain:1, level:2, question:"How does the second line of defense typically support risk management?", options:["By owning and operating the day-to-day business processes that create the risk by design","By providing fully independent assurance over the entire control environment","By designing frameworks, setting standards, and monitoring risk across the enterprise","By acting as the external regulator that enforces statutory compliance rules"], correct:2, explanation:"The second line designs frameworks and monitors risk. Owning processes is the first line, independent assurance is the third line, and regulators are external to the model." },
  { id:40144, domain:1, level:1, question:"What is the MAIN goal of aligning IT risk with business objectives?", options:["To make the IT department the final authority on all business strategy choices","To eliminate the need for business leaders to understand technology risk at all","To guarantee that the IT budget will always increase year over year going forward","To ensure technology risk decisions enable rather than hinder business goals"], correct:3, explanation:"Alignment ensures IT risk decisions enable business goals. It does not make IT the strategy authority, excuse business leaders from understanding risk, or guarantee budget growth." },
  { id:40145, domain:1, level:2, question:"Which of the following is an example of a 'business process' relevant to risk governance?", options:["Order-to-cash processing, which creates exposure that must be governed and managed","A single antivirus signature file stored on one endpoint in the network","The serial number printed on a piece of data center rack-mounted hardware by design","An individual log entry generated by a server during routine operation"], correct:0, explanation:"Order-to-cash is a business process carrying governable risk. A signature file, a serial number, and a single log entry are technical artifacts, not business processes." },
  { id:40146, domain:1, level:1, question:"An enterprise faces conflicting legal requirements across two jurisdictions. What governance step is MOST appropriate?", options:["Choosing to ignore the requirement from the jurisdiction with smaller revenue","Engaging legal counsel to reconcile obligations and update compliance requirements","Applying only the least strict requirement to minimize operational burden overall by design","Leaving the conflict unresolved and addressing it only if a regulator complains"], correct:1, explanation:"Engaging legal counsel to reconcile obligations is the governed approach. Ignoring one jurisdiction, applying the weakest rule, or waiting for complaints all create compliance exposure." },
  { id:40147, domain:1, level:3, question:"Why is it important to define risk tolerance for specific objectives?", options:["It guarantees that the objective will always be achieved without any deviation by design","It removes the need to set any enterprise-wide risk appetite whatsoever","It sets acceptable performance variation so deviations can be detected and managed","It applies only to financial objectives and never to operational outcomes"], correct:2, explanation:"Tolerance sets acceptable variation so deviations are managed. It does not guarantee achievement, replace appetite, or apply only to financial objectives." },
  { id:40148, domain:1, level:3, question:"What does the principle of 'segregation of duties' contribute to governance?", options:["It ensures that a single trusted person controls every step of a process","It removes the need for any management oversight of sensitive transactions by design","It applies only to the finance department and never to information systems","It reduces the risk of error and fraud by dividing critical responsibilities"], correct:3, explanation:"Segregation of duties divides responsibilities to reduce error and fraud. It is the opposite of single-person control, does not remove oversight, and applies beyond finance." },
  { id:40149, domain:1, level:1, question:"Who is typically responsible for implementing controls assigned by a risk response?", options:["The control owner, who is responsible for putting and keeping the control in place","The board of directors, which personally configures each technical safeguard by design","The external auditor, who designs and deploys the controls during fieldwork","The regulator, who installs the controls to enforce statutory requirements"], correct:0, explanation:"The control owner implements and maintains assigned controls. The board sets direction, external auditors assess, and regulators enforce; none implement controls." },
  { id:40150, domain:1, level:2, question:"A merger introduces a new business unit with an unknown risk profile. What governance action comes FIRST?", options:["Immediately decommissioning all of the new unit's systems to remove uncertainty","Assessing the unit against the enterprise framework to integrate its risk profile","Excluding the new unit from enterprise risk reporting until the next full fiscal year","Assuming the new unit's risk matches the existing units without any assessment"], correct:1, explanation:"Assessing the new unit against the framework integrates it properly. Decommissioning systems, excluding it from reporting, or assuming equivalence all ignore the unknown profile." },
  { id:40151, domain:1, level:3, question:"How do business processes relate to risk in a governance context?", options:["Processes are purely administrative and carry no risk worth governing at all","Processes only matter to operations and are irrelevant to risk governance work by design","Processes generate value and exposure, so their risks must be identified and governed","Processes replace the need for any risk assessment because they are documented"], correct:2, explanation:"Processes create both value and exposure, so their risks must be governed. They are not risk-free, not irrelevant to governance, and documentation does not replace assessment." },
  { id:40152, domain:1, level:3, question:"What is the PRIMARY value of a clearly communicated risk appetite?", options:["It guarantees that the organization will outperform every one of its competitors","It eliminates the need for managers to exercise any judgment in their decisions","It applies only to the executive team and is hidden from operational staff","It guides consistent risk-taking decisions across all levels of the enterprise"], correct:3, explanation:"A clear appetite guides consistent decisions enterprise-wide. It does not guarantee outperformance, remove the need for judgment, or apply only to executives." },
  { id:40153, domain:1, level:2, question:"What is meant by 'compliance requirement' in risk governance?", options:["An obligation arising from laws, regulations, contracts, or internal policies","A purely optional suggestion that the organization may freely choose to ignore","A technical metric describing the throughput of a particular network device","The personal goal set by an individual employee for their own performance"], correct:0, explanation:"A compliance requirement is an obligation from laws, regulations, contracts, or policies. It is not optional, not a technical throughput metric, and not a personal goal." },
  { id:40154, domain:1, level:1, question:"Risk decisions are being made inconsistently because no one knows who has authority. What is the BEST remedy?", options:["Allowing whoever responds first to make each risk decision as it arises","Defining a clear RACI for risk decisions so authority and accountability are set","Escalating absolutely every risk decision to the chief executive officer","Removing decision authority entirely and freezing all risk-related activity by design"], correct:1, explanation:"A clear RACI assigns decision authority and accountability. First-responder decisions, escalating everything to the CEO, or freezing activity all fail to fix the authority gap." },
  { id:40155, domain:1, level:2, question:"Why should risk governance consider the organization's reputation as an asset?", options:["Reputation has no measurable value and is therefore excluded from governance","Reputation is only the responsibility of the public relations team in isolation","Reputation has real value and damage to it can impair objectives and trust","Reputation is protected automatically and never requires any risk treatment"], correct:2, explanation:"Reputation is a valuable asset whose damage impairs objectives. It is not value-free, not solely PR's concern, and not automatically protected." },
  { id:40156, domain:1, level:1, question:"What role does senior management play in risk governance?", options:["Performing independent assurance reviews over its own management activities","Setting the enterprise risk appetite without any board involvement in any form whatsoever","Configuring every technical control personally across all production systems","Translating board direction into policies, resources, and risk management execution"], correct:3, explanation:"Senior management translates board direction into execution. It does not provide independent assurance over itself, set appetite without the board, or configure every control." },
  { id:40157, domain:1, level:3, question:"Which of the following is a 'legal requirement' an enterprise must govern?", options:["A statute requiring protection of personal data processed by the organization","A vendor's marketing claim about the speed of its newest product release","An internal preference for a particular brand of office productivity software","A team's informal habit of meeting on Friday afternoons each week"], correct:0, explanation:"A data-protection statute is a legal requirement. A marketing claim, a software preference, and an informal habit are not legally binding obligations." },
  { id:40158, domain:1, level:2, question:"The board asks how IT risk could affect strategic goals. Which response demonstrates BEST governance thinking?", options:["Listing the number of open vulnerabilities without tying them to any objective by design","Presenting risk scenarios mapped to each strategic goal and their potential impact","Providing a detailed firewall configuration export for the board to review","Stating that IT risk is purely technical and not relevant to strategic goals"], correct:1, explanation:"Mapping scenarios to strategic goals shows governance maturity. Raw vulnerability counts, firewall exports, or denying relevance all fail to connect risk to strategy." },
  { id:40159, domain:1, level:2, question:"What is the benefit of integrating risk appetite into project approval decisions?", options:["Every project is automatically approved because appetite removes the need to review","Project teams no longer need to consider risk during the planning phase at all","Projects exceeding acceptable risk are flagged before resources are committed","Risk appetite ensures all projects finish exactly on time and within budget"], correct:2, explanation:"Embedding appetite flags excessive-risk projects before commitment. It does not auto-approve projects, remove planning-phase risk thinking, or guarantee schedule and budget." },
  { id:40160, domain:1, level:3, question:"How does risk governance interact with the organization's strategy?", options:["Governance operates independently and never references the corporate strategy","Governance replaces strategy by dictating all business decisions to leadership by design","Governance is concerned only with technology and ignores corporate strategy","Governance ensures risk-taking stays aligned with strategic objectives and appetite"], correct:3, explanation:"Governance keeps risk-taking aligned with strategy and appetite. It is not independent of strategy, does not replace it, and is not limited to technology." },
  { id:40161, domain:1, level:2, question:"What is the purpose of a 'code of ethics' for risk professionals?", options:["To define expected standards of integrity, objectivity, and professional conduct","To list the specific technical certifications each professional must hold first by design","To set the salary ranges for risk roles across the entire industry sector","To replace the organization's policies and standards with personal opinion"], correct:0, explanation:"A code of ethics defines integrity and conduct standards. It does not list certifications, set salaries, or replace organizational policies." },
  { id:40162, domain:1, level:3, question:"An enterprise wants risk ownership embedded in the business rather than centralized in IT. What is the BEST approach?", options:["Keeping all risk ownership in IT because IT understands the systems the best by design","Assigning business risk owners who are accountable for risks in their own areas","Removing risk ownership entirely so no single person can be held accountable","Rotating ownership randomly each month so no owner becomes too comfortable"], correct:1, explanation:"Assigning business risk owners embeds ownership in the business. Centralizing in IT, removing ownership, or random rotation all weaken meaningful accountability." },
  { id:40163, domain:1, level:2, question:"Why is documenting policies and standards important for risk governance?", options:["Documentation guarantees that no risk event can ever occur in the organization","Documentation is needed only when an external auditor specifically requests it","Documentation provides a consistent, auditable basis for managing risk across staff","Documentation replaces the need for any training or awareness activities in any way at any time"], correct:2, explanation:"Documentation gives a consistent, auditable basis for managing risk. It cannot prevent all events, is needed beyond audits, and does not replace training." },
  { id:40164, domain:1, level:3, question:"What is the relationship between risk capacity and risk appetite?", options:["Appetite must always exceed capacity to ensure the enterprise grows aggressively by design","Capacity and appetite are unrelated concepts that never inform each other at all","Capacity is a subjective preference while appetite is a hard mathematical limit","Appetite should remain within capacity, the objective limit the enterprise can bear"], correct:3, explanation:"Appetite should stay within capacity, the objective bearable limit. Appetite should not exceed capacity, the two are related, and capacity is objective while appetite is the preference." },
  { id:40165, domain:1, level:2, question:"Which group is considered part of the 'first line of defense'?", options:["Operational staff and managers who own and manage risk in their daily work","Internal auditors who independently evaluate the design of the control set","External regulators who enforce compliance with mandated legal standards","Board committees that set the enterprise's overall risk oversight direction"], correct:0, explanation:"Operational staff and managers form the first line. Internal auditors are the third line, regulators are external, and board committees provide governance oversight, not the first line." },
  { id:40166, domain:1, level:2, question:"A company's risk policy has not changed in five years despite major business shifts. What is the PRIMARY concern?", options:["The policy is too short and should be expanded with additional technical detail by design","The policy may no longer reflect current objectives, threats, and the environment","The policy was written by the wrong department and should be reassigned now","The policy should be deleted because older documents have no remaining value"], correct:1, explanation:"A stale policy may no longer reflect current objectives and threats. Length, authorship, and outright deletion are not the primary governance concern here." },
  { id:40167, domain:1, level:3, question:"How does effective governance handle the relationship between risk and reward?", options:["It seeks to avoid all risk so that no exposure of any kind is ever accepted by design","It pursues maximum reward regardless of the level of risk being assumed","It enables informed risk-taking where potential reward justifies the exposure taken","It ignores reward entirely and focuses only on minimizing every exposure"], correct:2, explanation:"Good governance enables informed risk-taking where reward justifies exposure. Avoiding all risk, chasing reward blindly, or ignoring reward all misbalance the relationship." },
  { id:40168, domain:1, level:2, question:"What is the purpose of escalation procedures within risk governance?", options:["To slow down decisions so that no risk is ever acted upon too quickly","To route every minor operational issue directly to the board of directors by design","To remove accountability from managers by passing all decisions upward","To ensure significant risks reach the right decision-makers in a timely manner"], correct:3, explanation:"Escalation gets significant risks to the right decision-makers promptly. It is not meant to slow everything, route trivia to the board, or remove manager accountability." },
  { id:40169, domain:1, level:2, question:"What does 'accountability' mean in a risk governance context?", options:["Being answerable for outcomes of a risk decision and its associated results","Performing the hands-on technical work required to configure a control","Holding the documentation that describes how a process is meant to operate","Reviewing the work of others to provide independent assurance over controls"], correct:0, explanation:"Accountability means being answerable for outcomes. Performing technical work is responsibility, holding documentation is record-keeping, and independent review is assurance." },
  { id:40170, domain:1, level:2, question:"A regulator introduces new breach-notification timelines. Which governance update is MOST critical FIRST?", options:["Buying a new monitoring tool before assessing whether existing processes comply","Updating incident response policy and obligations to meet the new notification rule","Informing only the IT team and leaving business stakeholders entirely unaware","Waiting for the first breach to occur before reviewing the notification timeline by design"], correct:1, explanation:"Updating policy and obligations to meet the rule comes first. Buying tools prematurely, informing only IT, or waiting for a breach all leave the organization non-compliant." },
  { id:40171, domain:1, level:1, question:"Why is stakeholder identification important in risk governance?", options:["Stakeholders are only relevant when the organization is preparing to issue stock by design","Stakeholders have no role once the risk policy has been formally approved","Stakeholders influence and are affected by risk, so their interests must be considered","Stakeholders should be excluded to keep risk decisions simple and centralized"], correct:2, explanation:"Stakeholders influence and are affected by risk and must be considered. They matter beyond stock issuance, remain relevant after policy approval, and should not be excluded." },
  { id:40172, domain:1, level:3, question:"What is the role of the chief risk officer (CRO) in many organizations?", options:["To personally approve every individual purchase made across the organization","To serve as the independent external auditor of the company's financials","To manage the day-to-day technical operation of all production systems","To lead the enterprise risk function and advise leadership on risk matters"], correct:3, explanation:"A CRO leads the risk function and advises leadership. They do not approve all purchases, serve as external auditor, or run technical operations." },
  { id:40173, domain:1, level:2, question:"Which of the following BEST defines 'risk' in a governance context?", options:["The effect of uncertainty on the achievement of the organization's objectives","A guaranteed loss that the organization will certainly experience this year by design","A purely technical defect found only within software source code modules","An event that is always negative and can never present any opportunity"], correct:0, explanation:"Risk is the effect of uncertainty on objectives. It is not a guaranteed loss, not limited to software defects, and can present opportunity as well as threat." },
  { id:40174, domain:1, level:3, question:"Departments are duplicating risk activities with no coordination. Which governance improvement helps MOST?", options:["Letting each department keep working separately to preserve their independence","Establishing a central risk function to coordinate and standardize risk activities","Eliminating risk activities in all but one department to reduce the duplication by design","Assigning all risk work to external consultants on a permanent ongoing basis"], correct:1, explanation:"A central coordinating function standardizes and reduces duplication. Continued separation, eliminating activities elsewhere, or permanent outsourcing do not solve coordination." },
  { id:40175, domain:1, level:3, question:"How does risk governance support sound decision-making?", options:["By removing the need for managers to make any decisions about risk at all","By ensuring that every decision is delayed until all uncertainty disappears","By providing structure, information, and accountability so choices are well-informed","By centralizing all decisions with one individual to maximize the speed of action taken"], correct:2, explanation:"Governance provides structure, information, and accountability for informed choices. It does not remove decision-making, require zero uncertainty, or centralize everything in one person." },
  { id:40176, domain:1, level:2, question:"What is a key reason to define risk roles before launching a risk program?", options:["Defined roles guarantee that the program will require no budget to operate","Defined roles make it unnecessary to ever communicate with stakeholders again","Defined roles ensure the program will never need adjustment in the future","Clear roles prevent gaps and overlaps in who manages and oversees each risk"], correct:3, explanation:"Defining roles prevents gaps and overlaps in risk management. It does not eliminate budget needs, end stakeholder communication, or freeze the program from future change." },
  { id:40177, domain:1, level:3, question:"What is the purpose of an enterprise risk management (ERM) program?", options:["To manage risk holistically across the enterprise in support of its objectives","To handle only the cybersecurity risks affecting the technology environment by design","To replace the finance department's responsibility for the corporate budget","To eliminate the need for any insurance coverage held by the organization"], correct:0, explanation:"ERM manages risk holistically across the enterprise. It is broader than cybersecurity, does not replace finance, and does not eliminate the need for insurance." },
  { id:40178, domain:1, level:3, question:"An organization wants to ensure ethical behavior in risk reporting. Which control is MOST effective?", options:["A rule that only positive risk information may be presented to senior leadership","A whistleblower channel and code of conduct that protect honest risk disclosure","A policy that risk reports are reviewed solely by the person who created them","An incentive that rewards staff for reporting the fewest risks each quarter"], correct:1, explanation:"A whistleblower channel and code of conduct protect honest disclosure. Allowing only positive information, self-review, or rewarding fewer reports all encourage unethical reporting." },
  { id:40179, domain:1, level:2, question:"Why is it important for risk governance to consider organizational assets broadly?", options:["Because only physical hardware can ever be the subject of a risk assessment","Because intangible assets such as reputation cannot be affected by any risk","Because data, people, reputation, and processes all carry value and exposure","Because assets are relevant to accounting but never relevant to risk decisions"], correct:2, explanation:"A broad view covers data, people, reputation, and processes that all carry exposure. Limiting assets to hardware, dismissing intangibles, or excluding assets from risk are all wrong." },
  { id:40180, domain:1, level:2, question:"What distinguishes 'governance' from 'management' of risk?", options:["Governance executes daily tasks while management only observes from a distance by design","Governance and management are identical and the terms can be freely swapped","Governance applies to staff while management applies only to external parties","Governance sets direction and oversight, management executes within that direction"], correct:3, explanation:"Governance sets direction and oversight while management executes. The two are not reversed, not identical, and not split by staff versus external parties." },
  { id:40181, domain:1, level:3, question:"Which of the following is an example of 'risk tolerance' in practice?", options:["Allowing system downtime of up to four hours per month before action is needed","The broad statement that the firm is generally averse to operational risk","The total maximum financial loss the enterprise could possibly ever absorb by design","The shared values that shape how employees behave toward risk every day"], correct:0, explanation:"A specific downtime threshold is tolerance for an objective. The broad aversion statement is appetite, the maximum absorbable loss is capacity, and shared values are culture." },
  { id:40182, domain:1, level:3, question:"A risk owner repeatedly accepts risks beyond appetite without escalation. What governance gap does this reveal?", options:["A purely technical flaw in the configuration of the monitoring infrastructure","Weak enforcement of appetite limits and unclear escalation accountability for owners","An excess of internal audit activity slowing down the owner's daily decisions","An overly conservative appetite statement that should simply be widened broadly by design"], correct:1, explanation:"The gap is weak appetite enforcement and unclear escalation accountability. It is not a technical flaw, excessive audit, or a need to widen appetite to match misbehavior." },
  { id:40183, domain:1, level:2, question:"How should an organization treat a risk that falls within its stated appetite?", options:["It must always transfer the risk to an external insurer regardless of its size","It must escalate the risk to the board even though it is within appetite","It may accept and monitor the risk since it aligns with the agreed appetite","It should immediately apply the maximum possible controls to eliminate it"], correct:2, explanation:"Risk within appetite may be accepted and monitored. Mandatory transfer, mandatory board escalation, or maximum controls are unnecessary when the risk is within appetite." },
  { id:40184, domain:1, level:2, question:"Why is alignment between policies and regulatory requirements important?", options:["It guarantees the organization will never be audited by any regulator again","It allows the organization to ignore regulations it finds inconvenient to follow","It shifts all compliance accountability onto individual frontline employees","It ensures internal direction supports compliance and reduces legal exposure"], correct:3, explanation:"Alignment ensures policy supports compliance and limits legal exposure. It does not prevent audits, permit ignoring regulations, or push accountability onto frontline staff." },
  { id:40185, domain:1, level:2, question:"What is the purpose of assigning a risk owner to each significant risk?", options:["To create clear accountability for managing and responding to that specific risk","To ensure that no one is ever held responsible if the risk materializes badly by design","To transfer the technical work of control configuration to the audit function","To guarantee that the risk will be fully eliminated within the current year"], correct:0, explanation:"Assigning a risk owner creates clear accountability. It is the opposite of no responsibility, does not move work to audit, and does not guarantee elimination." },
  { id:40186, domain:1, level:3, question:"Senior leaders disagree on the enterprise risk appetite. Which governance mechanism should resolve this?", options:["Allowing each leader to apply a personal appetite within their own division","A board or risk committee decision that formally sets and approves the appetite","Deferring the decision indefinitely until all leaders happen to fully agree","Letting the most senior individual present unilaterally decide without record by design"], correct:1, explanation:"A board or risk committee formally sets appetite. Personal divisional appetites, indefinite deferral, or an undocumented unilateral call all bypass proper governance." },
  { id:40187, domain:1, level:2, question:"How does a strong risk culture benefit an organization?", options:["It ensures that employees never have to think about risk in their daily work by design","It allows the organization to remove all formal risk controls and oversight","It encourages timely identification and honest reporting of risks at all levels","It guarantees that the organization will never experience a loss event again"], correct:2, explanation:"A strong culture promotes timely identification and honest reporting. It does not excuse employees from thinking about risk, remove controls, or guarantee no losses." },
  { id:40188, domain:1, level:2, question:"What is the PRIMARY purpose of a risk governance policy?", options:["To document the exact technical configuration of every deployed security tool","To record the personal opinions of the risk team about specific vendors","To list the daily tasks performed by each member of the operations staff","To establish the principles and accountability for how risk will be managed"], correct:3, explanation:"A risk governance policy establishes principles and accountability for managing risk. It is not a technical configuration record, an opinion log, or a daily task list." },
  { id:40189, domain:1, level:2, question:"Which statement BEST describes the board's role regarding risk culture?", options:["The board sets the tone at the top that shapes the enterprise's risk culture","The board writes the detailed operating procedures for each business process","The board personally investigates every individual incident that is reported","The board approves each technical change deployed to production systems daily"], correct:0, explanation:"The board sets the tone at the top influencing culture. It does not write detailed procedures, investigate every incident, or approve daily technical changes." },
  { id:40190, domain:1, level:3, question:"An organization treats compliance and risk management as wholly separate silos. What is the BEST improvement?", options:["Keeping them separate so each team can focus narrowly on its own mandate","Integrating compliance obligations into the enterprise risk framework and reporting","Eliminating the compliance function and folding its duties into legal counsel by design","Reporting compliance only to regulators and never to internal risk governance"], correct:1, explanation:"Integrating compliance into the risk framework improves oversight. Keeping silos, eliminating compliance, or reporting only externally all weaken integrated governance." },
  { id:40191, domain:1, level:1, question:"Why should risk appetite be expressed in terms the business can understand?", options:["So the risk team can keep the appetite hidden from operational management","So the appetite never needs to be revisited once it is initially approved","So decision-makers can apply it when weighing real business choices","So only technical staff can interpret and apply the appetite in practice"], correct:2, explanation:"Business-understandable appetite enables consistent application by decision-makers. It is not meant to be hidden, frozen, or interpretable only by technical staff." },
  { id:40192, domain:1, level:2, question:"What is the benefit of mapping risks to the business objectives they affect?", options:["It guarantees that every mapped risk will be eliminated by year end automatically by design","It allows the risk team to ignore any risk that lacks an obvious objective link","It removes the need to assign owners because objectives own the risks themselves","It clarifies which objectives are threatened so prioritization reflects business value"], correct:3, explanation:"Mapping risks to objectives clarifies impact and supports value-based prioritization. It does not guarantee elimination, justify ignoring risks, or remove the need for owners." },
  { id:40193, domain:1, level:2, question:"Which of the following is a responsibility of the risk management function?", options:["Designing risk frameworks and monitoring the enterprise's overall risk exposure","Owning and operating each frontline business process that generates the risk","Providing fully independent assurance over the entire control environment alone","Enforcing statutory regulations as the official external government regulator"], correct:0, explanation:"The risk function designs frameworks and monitors exposure. Owning processes is the first line, independent assurance is the third line, and enforcement is the regulator's role." },
  { id:40194, domain:1, level:3, question:"Leadership asks how to know whether risk governance is effective. Which indicator is MOST meaningful?", options:["The risk register contains the largest possible number of documented entries","Risk decisions align with appetite and support strategic objectives","The risk team holds more meetings than any other department in the company","No risks have been reported at all during the most recent reporting period"], correct:1, explanation:"Decisions aligning with appetite and strategy indicate effective governance. A large register, frequent meetings, or zero reported risks are not meaningful effectiveness indicators." },
  { id:40195, domain:1, level:1, question:"How does risk governance address conflicts of interest among decision-makers?", options:["By ignoring conflicts since they rarely influence actual risk decisions made by design","By centralizing every decision with one person to avoid any disagreement","Through defined roles, segregation of duties, and ethical conduct requirements","By allowing decision-makers to police their own conflicts without oversight"], correct:2, explanation:"Defined roles, segregation, and ethics manage conflicts of interest. Ignoring them, centralizing in one person, or self-policing all increase conflict risk." },
  { id:40196, domain:1, level:1, question:"What is the value of communicating risk responsibilities throughout the organization?", options:["Only the risk team needs to know, so communication adds no real value at all","Communication guarantees that no employee will ever make a risk-related mistake by design","Communication replaces the need for any formal policies, standards, or training","Everyone understands their part, improving accountability and consistent risk handling"], correct:3, explanation:"Communicating responsibilities improves accountability and consistency. It is needed beyond the risk team, cannot prevent all mistakes, and does not replace policies or training." },
  { id:40197, domain:1, level:1, question:"What does 'tone at the top' refer to in risk governance?", options:["The example and attitude leadership sets that shapes risk behavior below them","The volume level used during executive meetings about risk-related matters","The technical baseline applied to the most senior executives' personal devices","The ranking order in which executives are listed on the organizational chart"], correct:0, explanation:"Tone at the top is the leadership example that shapes risk behavior. It is not meeting volume, a device baseline, or an org-chart ranking." },
  { id:40198, domain:1, level:1, question:"A subsidiary ignores the parent company's risk framework, citing local autonomy. What is the BEST governance response?", options:["Permitting the subsidiary to fully opt out of all enterprise risk requirements","Requiring alignment to the enterprise framework while allowing justified local tailoring","Dissolving the subsidiary immediately to remove the source of the disagreement","Ignoring the inconsistency because subsidiaries are outside enterprise governance by design"], correct:1, explanation:"Requiring alignment with justified local tailoring balances consistency and context. Full opt-out, dissolution, or ignoring the gap all undermine enterprise governance." },
  { id:40199, domain:1, level:2, question:"Why is it important to define both risk appetite and risk tolerance?", options:["Defining both is redundant because the two terms always mean the same thing","Only appetite matters because tolerance has no practical use in any decision","Appetite guides willingness while tolerance bounds variation per objective","Only tolerance matters because appetite is too vague to ever be applied at all"], correct:2, explanation:"Appetite guides willingness and tolerance bounds variation per objective, so both are needed. They are not redundant, and neither is useless on its own." },
  { id:40200, domain:1, level:3, question:"How does effective risk governance contribute to organizational resilience?", options:["By guaranteeing that the enterprise will never face any disruptive event again by design","By focusing only on recovering systems after an incident has already occurred","By transferring every conceivable risk to external third parties and insurers","By ensuring risks are anticipated and managed so the enterprise can adapt to disruption"], correct:3, explanation:"Governance builds resilience by anticipating and managing risk for adaptability. It cannot guarantee no disruption, is not only post-incident recovery, and is not blanket transfer." },
  { id:40201, domain:1, level:3, question:"What is the PRIMARY reason to involve business units in risk governance decisions?", options:["They understand their processes and objectives, enabling realistic risk decisions","They are the only group permitted to read the enterprise risk policy document","Their involvement removes the board entirely from any oversight responsibility","Their involvement guarantees that risk assessments will require no expert input by design"], correct:0, explanation:"Business units understand their processes, enabling realistic decisions. They are not the sole readers of policy, do not remove board oversight, and do not eliminate the need for expertise." },
  { id:40202, domain:1, level:1, question:"An enterprise lacks any formal risk appetite, and projects are approved inconsistently. What is the FIRST governance priority?", options:["Increasing the number of approval committees to slow risky projects down","Defining and approving a risk appetite to anchor consistent project decisions","Approving all pending projects quickly to clear the existing backlog first","Outsourcing all project risk decisions to an external advisory firm long term"], correct:1, explanation:"Defining and approving appetite anchors consistent decisions. More committees, clearing the backlog, or permanent outsourcing do not address the missing appetite foundation." },
  { id:40203, domain:1, level:2, question:"Which document type provides mandatory, specific requirements derived from a policy?", options:["A guideline that offers optional advice staff may follow at their own discretion by design","A procedure that lists the precise sequence of steps to complete a single task","A standard that translates policy intent into mandatory and specific requirements","A baseline report that records the current measured state of a given system"], correct:2, explanation:"A standard provides mandatory specific requirements from policy. A guideline is optional, a procedure is step sequence, and a baseline report records current state." },
  { id:40204, domain:1, level:2, question:"How does risk governance help balance innovation with prudent risk-taking?", options:["It blocks all innovation to ensure that no new risk is ever introduced at all","It allows unlimited innovation with no consideration of the risk being created by design","It restricts innovation to the risk team and excludes the rest of the business","It sets appetite and oversight so innovation proceeds within acceptable risk limits"], correct:3, explanation:"Governance lets innovation proceed within acceptable limits via appetite and oversight. It does not block all innovation, ignore risk, or confine innovation to the risk team." },
  { id:40205, domain:1, level:2, question:"What is the role of policies in shaping organizational risk culture?", options:["They signal expected behavior and reinforce the values leadership wants embedded","They have no effect on culture because culture is purely informal and unwritten by design","They replace the need for leadership to model any risk-aware behavior at all","They apply only to the legal team and never influence broader staff behavior"], correct:0, explanation:"Policies signal expected behavior and reinforce values, shaping culture. They do affect culture, do not replace leadership modeling, and apply beyond the legal team." },
  { id:40206, domain:1, level:2, question:"Who is typically responsible for providing independent assurance on risk management?", options:["Operational management, which owns and runs the processes that create the risk by design","Internal audit, which independently evaluates the effectiveness of risk processes","The risk function, which designs frameworks and monitors enterprise exposure","The board, which sets the overall strategic direction and the risk appetite"], correct:1, explanation:"Internal audit provides independent assurance as the third line. Operational management is the first line, the risk function is the second, and the board sets direction." },
  { id:40207, domain:1, level:2, question:"A risk practitioner is pressured to understate a risk to win project approval. What is the correct ethical response?", options:["Understate the risk this once because the project benefits the whole organization","Decline to assess the risk so no one can later question the reported figures","Report the risk accurately and escalate the pressure through appropriate channels","Report the risk accurately but only verbally so there is no written record"], correct:2, explanation:"Accurate reporting and escalating the pressure uphold ethics. Understating, refusing to assess, or avoiding a written record all compromise integrity and governance." },
  { id:40208, domain:1, level:2, question:"What does integrating risk into strategic planning achieve?", options:["Strategy is replaced entirely by the contents of the enterprise risk register","Planning becomes the sole responsibility of the risk management function alone","Risk is considered only after the strategy has been finalized and approved","Risks to strategy are identified early so plans account for them up front"], correct:3, explanation:"Integration identifies strategic risks early so plans account for them. It does not replace strategy, hand planning to the risk team, or defer risk until after approval." },
  { id:40209, domain:1, level:2, question:"Why should risk governance define clear ownership for organizational assets?", options:["Owners can be held accountable for protecting and managing each asset's risk","Ownership guarantees that the asset will never be subject to any threat at all","Ownership removes the asset from the scope of any future risk assessments","Ownership applies only to financial assets and never to data or systems"], correct:0, explanation:"Asset ownership establishes accountability for protecting each asset. It does not eliminate threats, exempt assets from assessment, or apply only to financial assets." },
  { id:40210, domain:1, level:2, question:"What is the purpose of a risk appetite statement?", options:["To list every technical control currently deployed across the organization","To communicate the level and type of risk the enterprise is willing to take","To record the outcome of each risk assessment performed during the year","To assign daily operational tasks to each member of the risk function staff"], correct:1, explanation:"A risk appetite statement communicates willingness to take risk. It is not a control inventory, an assessment-results log, or a task assignment list." },
  { id:40211, domain:1, level:2, question:"The board receives risk reports months after risks emerge, delaying decisions. What governance change helps MOST?", options:["Reducing the level of detail so reports can be produced faster but less accurately by design","Eliminating board risk reporting entirely to avoid the reporting delays altogether","Establishing timely reporting cadence and escalation so risks reach the board promptly","Reporting risks to the board only once per year to simplify the reporting process"], correct:2, explanation:"A timely cadence and escalation get risks to the board promptly. Cutting accuracy, eliminating reporting, or annual-only reporting all worsen oversight timeliness." },
  { id:40212, domain:1, level:2, question:"How does risk governance relate to organizational accountability?", options:["It diffuses accountability so that no single party can ever be held responsible by design","It applies accountability only to the most junior staff in each business unit","It removes accountability from managers and assigns it solely to the audit team","It assigns clear accountability so risk decisions can be traced to responsible parties"], correct:3, explanation:"Governance assigns clear, traceable accountability. It does not diffuse it, target only junior staff, or move all accountability to audit." },
  { id:40213, domain:1, level:3, question:"What is a benefit of aligning risk standards across the enterprise?", options:["Consistent risk treatment and comparability of exposures across all business units","Each business unit becoming entirely free to define its own conflicting standards by design","The complete removal of any need for local context in risk-related decisions","Standards becoming so rigid that no business activity can ever proceed safely"], correct:0, explanation:"Aligned standards give consistent treatment and comparable exposures. Conflicting local standards, ignoring all local context, or paralyzing rigidity are not the intended benefits." },
  { id:40214, domain:1, level:3, question:"Which of the following is part of 'organizational governance'?", options:["The specific antivirus signature updates pushed to endpoints each evening","The structures and processes by which the enterprise is directed and controlled","The individual log files generated by a single application server overnight by design","The seating arrangement of employees within the main corporate office space"], correct:1, explanation:"Organizational governance is the structures and processes directing and controlling the enterprise. Signature updates, log files, and seating are operational or trivial details." },
  { id:40215, domain:1, level:2, question:"An enterprise wants risk decisions to reflect both threats and opportunities. Which governance principle supports this?", options:["Defining risk strictly as a negative event so opportunities are excluded entirely","Allowing only the finance team to consider opportunity while others avoid it","Treating risk as the effect of uncertainty, encompassing both upside and downside","Separating opportunity management completely from the enterprise risk program"], correct:2, explanation:"Defining risk as uncertainty's effect captures upside and downside. Restricting risk to negatives, limiting opportunity to finance, or separating it all narrow the view." },
  { id:40216, domain:1, level:3, question:"Why is leadership commitment essential to effective risk governance?", options:["Leadership commitment guarantees that the program will need no funding to operate by design","Leadership involvement removes the need for any policies or defined standards","Leadership support matters only when an external regulator conducts an inspection","Leadership provides direction, resources, and the visible support that drives the program"], correct:3, explanation:"Leadership provides direction, resources, and visible support. Commitment does not eliminate funding needs, remove policies, or matter only during inspections." },
  { id:40217, domain:1, level:1, question:"What is the purpose of defining risk-related responsibilities in job descriptions?", options:["To embed risk accountability into roles so it is part of everyday expectations","To ensure that only the risk team ever has any responsibility for managing risk","To guarantee that employees will never need any further risk awareness training","To shift all risk decisions away from managers and onto frontline employees"], correct:0, explanation:"Embedding risk in job descriptions makes accountability part of daily roles. It does not confine risk to one team, end training needs, or push all decisions to frontline staff." },
  { id:40218, domain:1, level:2, question:"What does the 'three lines of defense' model primarily clarify?", options:["The exact sequence of steps required to recover a failed production database","The distinct roles for owning, overseeing, and assuring risk across the enterprise","The specific budget allocated to each department for purchasing new equipment by design","The physical layout of network segments within the corporate data center"], correct:1, explanation:"The model clarifies roles for owning, overseeing, and assuring risk. It is not a recovery sequence, a budget allocation, or a network layout." },
  { id:40219, domain:1, level:3, question:"Risk owners lack authority to act on the risks they own. What governance flaw does this indicate?", options:["An excessive level of authority granted to the internal audit function overall","A purely technical limitation in the configuration of the access control system by design","A mismatch between assigned accountability and the authority needed to act on it","An overly detailed risk register that should be simplified to fewer entries"], correct:2, explanation:"The flaw is misalignment of accountability and authority. It is not excess audit authority, a technical access limitation, or register complexity." },
  { id:40220, domain:1, level:3, question:"How does risk governance support meeting regulatory obligations?", options:["By assuming that regulators will overlook any gaps in the enterprise's compliance by design","By treating each regulation as a one-time task never revisited after completion","By delegating all regulatory responsibility to the most junior available staff","By maintaining accountability and processes that track and satisfy each obligation"], correct:3, explanation:"Governance tracks and satisfies obligations through accountability and process. Assuming regulator leniency, one-time treatment, or junior delegation all create compliance exposure." },
  { id:40221, domain:1, level:2, question:"What is the relationship between organizational culture and risk policies?", options:["Culture and policies reinforce each other to shape consistent risk behavior","Policies fully determine culture, so culture itself requires no separate attention","Culture fully determines policy, so written policies become entirely unnecessary","Culture and policies are unrelated and never influence one another in any way"], correct:0, explanation:"Culture and policies reinforce each other to shape behavior. Neither fully determines the other, and they are not unrelated." },
  { id:40222, domain:1, level:1, question:"Which of the following BEST describes a 'risk register'?", options:["A document that lists only the technical specifications of installed firewalls","A record of identified risks, their assessment, owners, and planned responses","A schedule showing the working hours of each member of the operations team","A contract that legally transfers risk to an external insurance company"], correct:1, explanation:"A risk register records identified risks, assessment, owners, and responses. It is not a firewall spec sheet, a staff schedule, or an insurance contract." },
  { id:40223, domain:1, level:2, question:"An organization's risk appetite is far below its capacity, stifling growth. What is the BEST governance consideration?", options:["Immediately raising appetite to match capacity without any board involvement in any way at any time","Lowering capacity to match the conservative appetite already in place currently","Reviewing whether appetite can be responsibly increased toward capacity to enable growth","Ignoring the gap because appetite should always remain far below capacity always"], correct:2, explanation:"Reviewing whether appetite can responsibly rise toward capacity supports growth. Raising it without the board, lowering capacity, or ignoring the gap are all poor responses." },
  { id:40224, domain:1, level:2, question:"Why is it important to communicate risk appetite across the organization?", options:["So the risk team alone can apply the appetite while others remain unaware of it by design","So the appetite can be changed informally by any manager whenever convenient","So that the board no longer needs to be involved in any risk-related decisions","So staff at all levels make decisions consistent with the enterprise's risk stance"], correct:3, explanation:"Communicating appetite enables consistent decisions at all levels. It is not for the risk team alone, not for informal change, and does not remove the board's role." },
  { id:40225, domain:1, level:3, question:"What is the purpose of a governance structure that separates oversight from execution?", options:["To provide objective oversight that is not compromised by those performing the work","To ensure that the people doing the work also independently assure that same work by design","To centralize both oversight and execution within a single individual for speed","To remove oversight entirely so that execution can proceed without any checks"], correct:0, explanation:"Separating oversight from execution preserves objectivity. Self-assurance, single-person centralization, or removing oversight all undermine independent governance." },
  { id:40226, domain:1, level:2, question:"What does 'risk awareness' refer to within an organization?", options:["The total number of antivirus alerts generated across all endpoints each day","The extent to which staff understand risks and their role in managing them","The precise monetary value assigned to a single asset in the risk register","The legal contract used to transfer a particular risk to a third-party vendor"], correct:1, explanation:"Risk awareness is staff understanding of risks and their role. It is not an alert count, a single asset value, or a transfer contract." },
  { id:40227, domain:1, level:1, question:"Leadership wants to ensure ethics are upheld across the risk program. Which governance element is MOST foundational?", options:["An annual quiz that staff complete and immediately forget after passing it","A poster campaign in hallways with no follow-up or accountability mechanism","A code of conduct supported by leadership example and enforced consequences","A policy that exists only on paper and is never communicated to any staff"], correct:2, explanation:"A code of conduct with leadership example and enforcement is foundational. A forgettable quiz, an unsupported poster campaign, or an uncommunicated policy lack real effect." },
  { id:40228, domain:1, level:2, question:"How does effective risk governance treat low-likelihood, high-impact risks?", options:["It ignores them entirely because they are unlikely to occur in any given year","It treats them identically to trivial risks with no special escalation at all","It assumes insurance alone fully addresses them without any further governance","It ensures they are identified, escalated, and addressed despite their rarity"], correct:3, explanation:"Such risks must be identified, escalated, and addressed despite rarity. Ignoring them, treating them as trivial, or relying solely on insurance are inadequate responses." },
  { id:40229, domain:1, level:3, question:"What is a key purpose of board-level risk oversight?", options:["To ensure management manages risk within the appetite the board has approved","To perform the detailed day-to-day risk assessments for each business process","To configure and maintain the technical controls protecting production systems","To act as the independent internal audit function for the entire enterprise"], correct:0, explanation:"Board oversight ensures management operates within approved appetite. The board does not perform detailed assessments, configure controls, or serve as internal audit." },
  { id:40230, domain:1, level:1, question:"Which of the following is an example of a regulatory compliance obligation?", options:["Following the personal preferences of a single manager for meeting formats","Meeting data-protection requirements imposed by an applicable privacy regulation","Adopting a vendor's recommended but non-mandatory product configuration tips by design","Choosing a particular color scheme for the corporate intranet home page"], correct:1, explanation:"Meeting privacy regulation requirements is a regulatory obligation. A manager's preference, a vendor's optional tips, and an intranet color scheme are not regulatory obligations." },
  { id:40231, domain:1, level:3, question:"An organization's risk roles overlap, causing confusion over who decides. What is the BEST governance correction?", options:["Allowing the overlapping roles to negotiate authority informally case by case","Merging all overlapping roles into one position regardless of workload concerns","Clarifying and documenting role boundaries so decision authority is unambiguous","Removing all the affected roles so the overlap problem disappears entirely now"], correct:2, explanation:"Clarifying and documenting role boundaries removes the confusion. Informal negotiation, forced merging, or removing roles all fail to establish clear authority." },
  { id:40232, domain:1, level:3, question:"Why should risk governance consider both internal and external stakeholders?", options:["Only internal stakeholders matter because external parties have no real interest","Only external stakeholders matter because they ultimately fund the organization","Stakeholders are irrelevant once the enterprise risk policy has been approved","Both groups affect and are affected by risk, shaping appropriate risk responses"], correct:3, explanation:"Both internal and external stakeholders affect and are affected by risk. It is not internal-only, external-only, or irrelevant after policy approval." },
  { id:40233, domain:1, level:3, question:"What is the benefit of linking risk reporting to business objectives?", options:["Decision-makers see which objectives are at risk and can prioritize accordingly","Reports become longer and more technical, demonstrating the team's deep effort","Reporting can then be limited to the technology department without business input","Objectives no longer need owners because the reports describe them in full detail"], correct:0, explanation:"Linking reporting to objectives shows which goals are at risk for prioritization. It is not about length, limiting to IT, or removing the need for objective owners." },
  { id:40234, domain:1, level:2, question:"Who sets the overall direction for an organization's risk management approach?", options:["The help desk technicians, who resolve user-reported incidents during each shift by design","The board and senior leadership, who establish direction, appetite, and oversight","The external penetration testers engaged for an annual assessment exercise","The vendors who supply the organization's commercial software applications"], correct:1, explanation:"The board and senior leadership set direction, appetite, and oversight. Technicians, external testers, and vendors do not set the enterprise risk direction." },
  { id:40235, domain:1, level:1, question:"A company wants to ensure IT investments support strategy and stay within risk appetite. Which governance practice helps MOST?", options:["Approving every IT investment that any department requests without any review","Letting the IT team decide all investments independently of business strategy","Integrating risk appetite into IT investment and portfolio governance decisions","Deferring all IT investment decisions until the next annual planning cycle only"], correct:2, explanation:"Embedding appetite into investment governance aligns IT spend with strategy and risk. Blanket approval, IT-only decisions, or deferral all weaken alignment." },
  { id:40236, domain:1, level:3, question:"How does risk governance support consistency in decision-making?", options:["By allowing each decision-maker to invent a new approach for every situation","By centralizing every decision so only one person ever makes any choice at all","By removing all guidance so decisions can be made as quickly as possible in every single instance","By providing shared frameworks, appetite, and roles that guide decisions uniformly"], correct:3, explanation:"Shared frameworks, appetite, and roles guide uniform decisions. Inventing new approaches, single-person centralization, or removing guidance all reduce consistency." },
  { id:40237, domain:1, level:2, question:"What is the purpose of periodic review of the risk governance framework?", options:["To keep the framework aligned with changing objectives, threats, and regulations","To reset the entire risk register to empty at the start of each review cycle","To prove that the framework will never need to be changed again at any point in the future","To satisfy auditors with paperwork while changing nothing about the approach"], correct:0, explanation:"Periodic review keeps the framework aligned with change. It is not about resetting the register, proving permanence, or producing meaningless paperwork." },
  { id:40238, domain:1, level:2, question:"Which of the following describes 'risk capacity' correctly?", options:["The subjective amount of risk leadership would prefer to take to pursue value","The objective maximum level of risk an enterprise can absorb given its resources","The acceptable variation tolerated around a single specific business objective by design","The shared attitudes and behaviors of staff toward risk in their daily work"], correct:1, explanation:"Risk capacity is the objective maximum absorbable given resources. Preference is appetite, variation around an objective is tolerance, and shared attitudes are culture." },
  { id:40239, domain:1, level:3, question:"Two risk owners both claim responsibility for the same risk, creating duplication. What is the BEST resolution?", options:["Letting both owners continue independently to ensure the risk gets extra attention","Removing both owners so the risk reverts to the risk management team by default","Assigning a single accountable owner and clarifying any supporting roles clearly","Escalating the dispute to external auditors to decide who should own the risk"], correct:2, explanation:"A single accountable owner with clarified supporting roles resolves duplication. Dual independent owners, removing both, or asking external auditors to decide are inappropriate." },
  { id:40240, domain:1, level:1, question:"Why is it important to align risk management with the organization's mission?", options:["Alignment guarantees that the organization will never face any competitive threat","Alignment lets the risk function operate without input from any business leaders","Alignment removes the requirement to comply with applicable laws and regulations","Alignment ensures risk decisions ultimately support the enterprise's core purpose"], correct:3, explanation:"Aligning risk with mission ensures decisions support core purpose. It does not eliminate competitive threats, exclude business input, or remove legal compliance." },
  { id:40241, domain:1, level:1, question:"What does a mature risk culture typically demonstrate?", options:["Open communication about risk and consistent risk-aware behavior across all levels","Reluctance to report any bad news for fear of management punishment or blame","Risk discussion confined to a single annual meeting attended only by executives by design","Complete reliance on automated tools with no human judgment about risk at all"], correct:0, explanation:"A mature culture shows open communication and consistent risk-aware behavior. Fear of reporting, confined discussion, or no human judgment all indicate immaturity." },
  { id:40242, domain:1, level:1, question:"What is the role of 'policies and standards' in supporting governance objectives?", options:["They serve only as decorative documents with no influence on actual operations by design","They translate governance intent into actionable rules that guide consistent behavior","They apply exclusively to the IT department and never to other business areas","They eliminate the need for leadership to communicate any expectations at all"], correct:1, explanation:"Policies and standards translate intent into actionable rules. They are not decorative, not IT-only, and do not remove the need for leadership communication." },
  { id:40243, domain:1, level:2, question:"An enterprise faces increasing regulatory scrutiny and wants stronger governance. Which step is MOST impactful FIRST?", options:["Hiring many additional staff before defining who is accountable for compliance","Purchasing automated compliance tools before assessing actual obligations in any way at any time","Establishing clear accountability and a compliance framework integrated with risk","Assuring regulators verbally that the enterprise intends to comply in the future"], correct:2, explanation:"Clear accountability and an integrated compliance framework is most impactful. Hiring first, buying tools first, or verbal assurances do not build the needed foundation." },
  { id:40244, domain:1, level:2, question:"How does risk governance handle the diversity of risks across business units?", options:["By forcing every unit to use identical responses regardless of its actual context","By letting each unit operate with no common framework or shared expectations","By managing only the risks of the largest unit and ignoring all smaller units","Through a common framework that allows tailoring to each unit's specific context"], correct:3, explanation:"A common framework with tailoring handles diversity well. Identical forced responses, no common framework, or ignoring smaller units all fail to balance consistency and context." },
  { id:40245, domain:1, level:2, question:"What is the purpose of defining a risk management strategy?", options:["To set the approach and priorities for managing risk in support of objectives","To list the serial numbers of every hardware device owned by the enterprise","To record the daily attendance of each employee within the risk department","To replace the corporate strategy with a document focused only on avoiding risk"], correct:0, explanation:"A risk management strategy sets the approach and priorities supporting objectives. It is not a hardware inventory, an attendance log, or a replacement for corporate strategy." },
  { id:40246, domain:1, level:1, question:"Which statement BEST reflects the relationship between IT risk and business objectives?", options:["IT risk is purely technical and has no connection to the achievement of objectives","IT risk can threaten or enable business objectives and must be managed accordingly","Business objectives are set by the IT team based on the available technology only","IT risk only becomes relevant after a business objective has already been missed"], correct:1, explanation:"IT risk can threaten or enable objectives and must be managed in that light. It is not purely technical, IT does not set objectives, and it is relevant before objectives are missed." },
  { id:40247, domain:1, level:2, question:"A risk practitioner notices the risk framework conflicts with a new privacy law. What should they do FIRST?", options:["Continue using the existing framework and hope the conflict is never noticed","Quietly disregard the new law because the framework was approved earlier first by design","Raise the conflict so the framework can be updated to meet the legal requirement","Wait for a regulator to identify the conflict before taking any action at all"], correct:2, explanation:"Raising the conflict to update the framework upholds compliance. Continuing as-is, disregarding the law, or waiting for a regulator all create legal and governance exposure." },
  { id:40248, domain:1, level:2, question:"Why is executive sponsorship important for a risk governance initiative?", options:["It guarantees that the initiative will require no ongoing effort once it is launched","It allows the initiative to bypass all policies and standards already in effect","It ensures the initiative is confined entirely within the risk management team","It provides authority, resources, and credibility needed for adoption"], correct:3, explanation:"Executive sponsorship provides authority, resources, and credibility. It does not eliminate ongoing effort, allow bypassing policies, or confine the initiative to one team." },
  { id:40249, domain:1, level:2, question:"What is the benefit of a consistent risk taxonomy across the enterprise?", options:["Risks can be categorized and compared uniformly, improving aggregation and reporting","Each department can define risk terms differently to suit its own local preferences by design","The taxonomy removes the need to assess any risk because terms are standardized","The taxonomy applies only to financial risk and excludes all operational risk types"], correct:0, explanation:"A consistent taxonomy enables uniform categorization, aggregation, and reporting. Divergent terms, replacing assessment, or finance-only scope all undermine that benefit." },
  { id:40250, domain:1, level:3, question:"What does 'tone from the top' influence within an organization?", options:["The exact technical settings applied to each server in the production environment by design","The risk culture and behaviors that employees adopt by following leadership's example","The vendor selected to supply the organization's office furniture and supplies","The physical temperature maintained inside the corporate data center facility"], correct:1, explanation:"Tone from the top influences risk culture and behaviors. It does not set server configurations, choose furniture vendors, or control data center temperature." },
  { id:40251, domain:1, level:1, question:"An organization's policies are comprehensive but ignored in practice. What governance issue is MOST likely present?", options:["An excess of detail in the policies that makes them too thorough to be effective by design","A lack of additional policies covering the same topics already addressed fully","A weak risk culture and inadequate enforcement that undermine the written policies","A surplus of internal audit reviews that has overwhelmed the operational staff"], correct:2, explanation:"Ignored policies usually reflect weak culture and poor enforcement. Excess detail, missing duplicate policies, or too much audit are not the most likely root cause." },
  { id:40252, domain:1, level:2, question:"How does risk governance balance the interests of different stakeholders?", options:["By always prioritizing the single stakeholder who shouts the loudest each time","By ignoring stakeholder interests so decisions can be made faster and simpler","By delegating all stakeholder balancing to an external consulting firm permanently","By weighing stakeholder needs against objectives and appetite to guide decisions"], correct:3, explanation:"Governance weighs stakeholder needs against objectives and appetite. Favoring the loudest, ignoring interests, or permanent outsourcing all fail to balance stakeholders properly." },
  { id:40253, domain:1, level:2, question:"What is the purpose of aligning the risk framework with recognized standards?", options:["To leverage proven practices and improve credibility, comparability, and completeness","To guarantee certification that exempts the enterprise from all future audits","To make the framework so rigid that it can never adapt to the organization","To replace the enterprise's own objectives with the goals of the standard itself by design"], correct:0, explanation:"Aligning with recognized standards leverages proven practices and improves credibility. It does not exempt from audits, force rigidity, or override enterprise objectives." },
  { id:40254, domain:1, level:2, question:"Which of the following is a responsibility of a control owner?", options:["Setting the overall enterprise risk appetite on behalf of the board of directors","Ensuring the assigned control operates as intended and remains effective","Accepting the residual risk that remains after the control has been implemented","Providing independent assurance over the entire enterprise control environment"], correct:1, explanation:"A control owner ensures the control operates effectively. Setting appetite is the board's role, accepting residual risk is the risk owner's, and independent assurance is audit's." },
  { id:40255, domain:1, level:3, question:"Senior management wants assurance that risk governance is embedded, not just documented. Which evidence is MOST convincing?", options:["A large binder of policies that has been signed but never referenced in decisions","A single training session delivered once to staff several years previously now","Risk considerations appearing in real strategic and operational decisions","An organizational chart that lists a risk committee that has never actually met"], correct:2, explanation:"Risk appearing in real decisions shows genuine embedding. A signed-but-unused binder, an old one-time training, or a non-meeting committee are documentation without practice." },
  { id:40256, domain:1, level:2, question:"Why should risk governance address emerging risks proactively?", options:["Emerging risks are always trivial and therefore never warrant any advance attention by design","Addressing them early removes the need to ever monitor existing known risks again","Proactive attention transfers all emerging risk automatically to external insurers","Early identification allows the enterprise to prepare before the risk fully materializes"], correct:3, explanation:"Proactively addressing emerging risk allows preparation before impact. Emerging risks are not always trivial, monitoring known risks still matters, and it does not auto-transfer risk." },
  { id:40257, domain:1, level:1, question:"What is the value of integrating risk governance with corporate strategy execution?", options:["Risk-informed execution increases the likelihood of achieving strategic objectives","Strategy execution becomes the sole responsibility of the risk management function","Risk is considered only after strategic initiatives have completely failed already","Integration removes the need for any performance measurement of the strategy"], correct:0, explanation:"Risk-informed execution improves the odds of meeting objectives. It does not hand execution to the risk team, defer risk until failure, or remove performance measurement." },
  { id:40258, domain:1, level:3, question:"What is the primary focus of 'organizational governance'?", options:["Configuring the technical settings of individual workstations across the company by design","Directing and controlling the enterprise to achieve objectives responsibly and ethically","Scheduling the daily shifts for staff working in the customer support center","Selecting which brand of coffee is provided in the corporate break rooms"], correct:1, explanation:"Organizational governance focuses on directing and controlling the enterprise toward objectives. Workstation settings, shift scheduling, and coffee selection are operational trivia." },
  { id:40259, domain:1, level:3, question:"A company's risk function reports to the team it is meant to oversee, harming objectivity. What is the BEST fix?", options:["Keeping the existing reporting line because it makes day-to-day coordination easier by design","Disbanding the risk function so the conflict of interest disappears entirely now","Establishing an independent reporting line so oversight is not compromised by conflict","Asking the overseen team to self-assess and report on its own risk performance"], correct:2, explanation:"An independent reporting line preserves objectivity. Keeping the conflicted line, disbanding the function, or relying on self-assessment all perpetuate the conflict of interest." },
  { id:40260, domain:1, level:3, question:"How does risk governance contribute to stakeholder confidence?", options:["By concealing all risk information so stakeholders never see any negative news by design","By promising stakeholders that no risk event will ever affect the enterprise","By delegating all stakeholder communication to the marketing team exclusively","By demonstrating that risks are identified and managed in a structured, transparent way"], correct:3, explanation:"Structured, transparent risk management builds stakeholder confidence. Concealment, impossible promises, or marketing-only communication do not genuinely build confidence." },
  { id:40261, domain:1, level:1, question:"What is the purpose of a risk policy approval process?", options:["To ensure policies are reviewed and authorized by parties with appropriate authority","To slow down the publication of policies for no defined governance reason in any way at any time","To allow any employee to publish a policy without any review or oversight first","To transfer all policy accountability to the external auditor who reviews them"], correct:0, explanation:"An approval process ensures appropriate authority reviews and authorizes policies. It is not pointless delay, unrestricted publishing, or transferring accountability to auditors." },
  { id:40262, domain:1, level:3, question:"Which group typically performs the day-to-day management of risk in their processes?", options:["Third-line internal auditors who independently assess the control environment overall","First-line operational staff who own and run the processes that generate the risk","External regulators who enforce statutory and industry compliance requirements","Board committees that set the enterprise's strategic direction and risk appetite"], correct:1, explanation:"First-line operational staff manage risk day to day. Internal auditors are the third line, regulators are external, and board committees set direction." },
  { id:40263, domain:1, level:2, question:"An organization wants its risk appetite to remain relevant amid rapid market change. What governance practice supports this BEST?", options:["Locking the appetite permanently so it provides a fixed and unchanging reference point","Allowing each manager to interpret the outdated appetite however they see fit locally","Reviewing and adjusting appetite regularly as objectives and conditions evolve","Delegating appetite adjustments to frontline staff without any board oversight at all"], correct:2, explanation:"Regular review keeps appetite relevant amid change. Permanent locking, divergent interpretation, or unsupervised frontline adjustment all reduce relevance and control." },
  { id:40264, domain:1, level:1, question:"Why is it important to distinguish between accountability and responsibility in risk governance?", options:["The two terms are identical and the distinction has no practical governance value","Accountability applies only to staff while responsibility applies only to the board by design","Responsibility can be delegated but accountability is impossible to ever delegate","Accountability is answerability for outcomes, responsibility is performing the work itself"], correct:3, explanation:"Accountability is answerability for outcomes while responsibility is doing the work. The terms are not identical, not split by role that way; though accountability indeed cannot be delegated, the defining distinction is answerability versus performing." },
  { id:40265, domain:1, level:1, question:"What does effective risk governance require regarding legal and regulatory change?", options:["Ongoing monitoring so the enterprise can adapt policies and controls to new obligations","A one-time review at company founding that never needs to be repeated thereafter","Complete reliance on regulators to notify the enterprise of every relevant change by design","Ignoring changes until a fine is issued and then reacting only at that point"], correct:0, explanation:"Ongoing monitoring lets the enterprise adapt to new obligations. A one-time review, total reliance on regulators, or waiting for fines all leave the enterprise exposed." },
  { id:40266, domain:1, level:2, question:"What is the role of 'business processes' in the context of risk governance?", options:["They are purely administrative records that carry no risk relevant to governance","They create value and exposure, so their risks must be identified and overseen","They are managed only by the IT department regardless of which function owns them","They eliminate risk automatically once they have been documented in a procedure"], correct:1, explanation:"Business processes create value and exposure requiring oversight. They are not risk-free records, not IT-owned by default, and documentation does not eliminate risk." },
  { id:40267, domain:1, level:3, question:"A board wants confidence that management's risk appetite matches its own. Which governance mechanism BEST provides this?", options:["Allowing management to set appetite independently and inform the board only afterward by design","Relying on informal hallway conversations between the board and management as needed","Formal board approval of the appetite statement followed by periodic reporting against it","Assuming alignment exists because management and the board share the same objectives"], correct:2, explanation:"Board approval plus periodic reporting against appetite ensures alignment. Independent management setting, informal conversations, or assumed alignment all leave a governance gap." },
  { id:40268, domain:1, level:2, question:"How does risk governance support the protection of organizational assets?", options:["By guaranteeing that no asset will ever be lost, damaged, or compromised in any way","By focusing only on physical assets while ignoring data, people, and reputation","By transferring responsibility for all assets to the procurement department alone","By assigning ownership and accountability so each asset's risk is managed"], correct:3, explanation:"Governance assigns ownership and accountability to manage asset risk. It cannot guarantee no loss, should not ignore intangible assets, or move all responsibility to procurement." },
  { id:40269, domain:1, level:1, question:"What is the benefit of clearly separating risk ownership from control ownership?", options:["It clarifies who accepts risk versus who maintains controls, improving accountability","It allows the same person to both accept risk and assure the controls without conflict","It removes the need for any oversight because the two roles cancel each other out","It applies only to financial controls and has no relevance to information systems"], correct:0, explanation:"Separating risk and control ownership clarifies who accepts risk versus maintains controls. It does not enable conflicted self-assurance, remove oversight, or apply only to finance." },
  { id:40270, domain:1, level:2, question:"Which of the following BEST describes the purpose of risk governance reporting?", options:["To document the technical configuration of every firewall deployed on the network by design","To inform decision-makers about the enterprise's risk status and support sound choices","To record the personal preferences of individual employees about specific tools","To list the daily lunch schedule for staff working in the risk department area"], correct:1, explanation:"Risk governance reporting informs decision-makers about risk status. It is not a firewall configuration log, a preference record, or a lunch schedule." },
  { id:40271, domain:1, level:1, question:"An enterprise wants ethics embedded so risk is never deliberately understated. Which combination is MOST effective?", options:["A single annual reminder email with no supporting channels, example, or consequences by design","A policy stating ethics matter that is filed away and never referenced in practice","A clear code of conduct, leadership example, safe reporting channels, and real consequences","An assumption that all staff are honest, so no ethics controls are needed at all"], correct:2, explanation:"A code of conduct, leadership example, safe reporting, and consequences together embed ethics. A lone email, an unused policy, or assuming honesty all leave ethics unsupported." },
  { id:40272, domain:1, level:2, question:"Why should risk governance be tailored to the size and complexity of the organization?", options:["Every organization must adopt the exact same heavyweight framework regardless of size by design","Smaller organizations need no risk governance because their risks are always trivial","Larger organizations should simplify governance to match the smallest competitor's","A proportionate approach ensures governance is effective without being unduly burdensome"], correct:3, explanation:"Proportionate governance is effective without excess burden. A one-size framework, no governance for small firms, or over-simplifying large firms all misjudge proportionality." },
  { id:40273, domain:1, level:1, question:"What is the purpose of escalating risks that exceed defined tolerance levels?", options:["To ensure higher authority reviews and decides on risks beyond acceptable variation","To slow down operations so that no business activity can proceed past a threshold","To shift accountability for the breach away from the responsible risk owner entirely","To create paperwork that satisfies auditors without prompting any real decision"], correct:0, explanation:"Escalation ensures higher authority decides on out-of-tolerance risks. It is not meant to halt operations, shift accountability away from owners, or generate empty paperwork." },
  { id:40274, domain:1, level:2, question:"Which of the following is an element of enterprise risk management governance?", options:["The specific brand of laptop issued to each new employee upon their hiring date by design","Defined roles, appetite, frameworks, and oversight that direct how risk is managed","The exact wording of every marketing email sent to prospective new customers","The seating chart used for the annual company holiday celebration gathering"], correct:1, explanation:"Roles, appetite, frameworks, and oversight are ERM governance elements. Laptop brands, marketing email wording, and seating charts are not governance elements." },
  { id:40275, domain:1, level:1, question:"A company's three lines of defense overlap, with audit also designing controls. What is the BEST governance correction?", options:["Allowing audit to keep designing controls because it understands them most deeply","Merging audit with operational management to streamline the overall reporting lines by design","Restoring audit's independence so it assures rather than designs the controls it reviews","Eliminating the second line so audit can absorb its framework duties completely"], correct:2, explanation:"Restoring audit's independence keeps it from assuring its own work. Letting audit design controls, merging it with operations, or absorbing the second line all break independence." },
  { id:40276, domain:1, level:2, question:"How does risk governance help an organization respond to regulatory examinations?", options:["By assuming that examiners will not request any documentation during their review by design","By preparing evidence only after the examination has already begun on site","By relying on a single employee's memory to answer all examiner questions live","By maintaining documented accountability, processes, and evidence of risk management"], correct:3, explanation:"Documented accountability, processes, and evidence support examinations. Assuming no requests, last-minute preparation, or reliance on memory all leave the enterprise unprepared." },
  { id:40277, domain:1, level:2, question:"What is the purpose of defining risk-related authority levels?", options:["To specify who may accept, escalate, or treat risks at each level of the organization","To ensure that only the chief executive may make any risk decision at any level by design","To remove all decision authority so risks are never acted upon by anyone at all","To assign every risk decision to the external auditor regardless of its nature"], correct:0, explanation:"Defined authority levels specify who may accept, escalate, or treat risks. Limiting all decisions to the CEO, removing authority, or assigning everything to auditors are inappropriate." },
  { id:40278, domain:1, level:3, question:"Which statement BEST describes the relationship between governance and risk appetite?", options:["Risk appetite replaces governance once it has been documented and approved formally by design","Governance establishes and oversees the risk appetite that guides enterprise decisions","Governance and risk appetite are unrelated concepts that never interact in practice","Risk appetite is set by frontline staff without any governance involvement at all"], correct:1, explanation:"Governance establishes and oversees the appetite guiding decisions. Appetite does not replace governance, they are related, and appetite is not set by frontline staff alone." },
  { id:40279, domain:1, level:3, question:"An enterprise's risk policies are strong but staff lack awareness of them. What is the BEST governance action?", options:["Adding more detailed policies on top of the ones staff already do not know about","Assuming awareness will develop naturally over time without any deliberate effort","Implementing ongoing awareness and training so staff understand and apply the policies","Restricting the policies to management so frontline staff need not be aware of them by design"], correct:2, explanation:"Ongoing awareness and training close the knowledge gap. Adding more unknown policies, assuming natural awareness, or restricting policies to management all leave staff uninformed." },
  { id:40280, domain:1, level:3, question:"Why is it important for risk governance to consider the organization's strategic objectives?", options:["Objectives are irrelevant to risk because risk is purely a technical security concern by design","Objectives are set by the risk function rather than by the business and its leaders","Objectives should be ignored so risk management can focus only on avoiding all loss","Risk decisions must support objectives, so objectives anchor what risk-taking is acceptable"], correct:3, explanation:"Strategic objectives anchor acceptable risk-taking. They are not irrelevant, not set by the risk function, and should not be ignored in favor of pure loss avoidance." },
  { id:40281, domain:1, level:3, question:"What does a 'risk-aware' decision-making process involve?", options:["Considering relevant risks and appetite before committing to a course of action","Ignoring risk entirely so decisions can be made as quickly as humanly possible","Deferring every decision until all possible risk has been completely eliminated","Allowing only the risk team to make any decision affecting the entire business"], correct:0, explanation:"Risk-aware decisions consider relevant risks and appetite first. Ignoring risk, waiting for zero risk, or restricting all decisions to the risk team are not risk-aware approaches." },
  { id:40282, domain:1, level:3, question:"Who is generally responsible for setting the organizational risk culture?", options:["The newest employees, who establish the cultural norms for everyone else to adopt by design","Senior leadership and the board, who set the example others across the firm follow","External auditors, who define how the organization should behave toward its risks","Software vendors, who shape culture through the tools they sell to the enterprise"], correct:1, explanation:"Senior leadership and the board set the example shaping risk culture. New employees, external auditors, and vendors do not set the enterprise's risk culture." },
  { id:40283, domain:1, level:2, question:"A company wants to ensure risk decisions can withstand regulatory and stakeholder scrutiny. Which governance attribute matters MOST?", options:["Speed of decision-making prioritized above any record of the reasoning involved","Confidentiality so tight that no decision rationale is ever recorded anywhere","Transparency and documented accountability showing how and why decisions were made","Delegation of all scrutinized decisions to external parties to avoid responsibility"], correct:2, explanation:"Transparency and documented accountability withstand scrutiny. Prioritizing pure speed, recording nothing, or delegating to avoid responsibility all weaken defensibility." },
  { id:40284, domain:1, level:3, question:"How does risk governance support consistency between policies and actual practice?", options:["By publishing policies once and assuming behavior will conform without any follow-up","By allowing practice to drift freely from policy as long as the policy still exists","By measuring only whether policies exist, never whether they are followed in practice by design","Through communication, training, monitoring, and enforcement that align behavior to policy"], correct:3, explanation:"Communication, training, monitoring, and enforcement align practice to policy. Publish-and-forget, tolerating drift, or measuring only existence all permit a policy-practice gap." },
  { id:40285, domain:1, level:2, question:"What is the purpose of a governance framework defining risk responsibilities at each level?", options:["To ensure risk is owned and managed appropriately from the board down to operations","To concentrate every risk responsibility within a single team at one level only","To remove risk responsibility from operational staff and give it only to the board","To make risk responsibility optional so individuals may decline it whenever they wish"], correct:0, explanation:"Defining responsibilities at each level ensures appropriate ownership board-to-operations. Concentrating, removing operational ownership, or making it optional all break the model." },
  { id:40286, domain:1, level:2, question:"Which of the following is a key output of effective risk governance?", options:["A complete elimination of every uncertainty affecting the enterprise's operations","Informed risk decisions that align with the enterprise's appetite and objectives","A guarantee that the organization will outperform all competitors in its market","A reduction of the organization's entire workforce to cut the cost of operations"], correct:1, explanation:"Informed decisions aligned to appetite and objectives are a key output. Governance cannot eliminate uncertainty, guarantee market outperformance, or aim to cut the workforce." },
  { id:40287, domain:1, level:3, question:"An organization discovers its risk appetite was set without considering capacity. What is the PRIMARY risk of this gap?", options:["Appetite would automatically become more conservative than is necessary for growth","Capacity would be permanently increased to whatever level appetite happens to require by design","Appetite could exceed what the enterprise can actually absorb, threatening its viability","The risk register would need to be deleted and rebuilt entirely from scratch now"], correct:2, explanation:"Without capacity, appetite could exceed what the enterprise can absorb, threatening viability. It does not auto-conservatize appetite, raise capacity, or require deleting the register." },
  { id:40288, domain:1, level:3, question:"Why should risk governance address third-party and supply chain risks?", options:["Third-party risk belongs entirely to the vendor and never concerns the enterprise itself by design","Supply chain risk is purely a logistics issue with no connection to risk governance","Third parties are outside the enterprise, so their risks require no oversight at all","Third parties can introduce exposure that affects the enterprise's objectives and obligations"], correct:3, explanation:"Third parties introduce exposure affecting enterprise objectives and obligations. The risk is not solely the vendor's, not merely logistics, and not exempt from oversight." },
  { id:40289, domain:1, level:3, question:"What is the benefit of integrating risk appetite into performance management?", options:["Performance goals account for acceptable risk, discouraging objectives pursued recklessly","Performance becomes the only factor considered, with risk disregarded entirely in every single instance","Risk appetite replaces performance targets so results no longer need to be measured","Performance management becomes the sole responsibility of the risk team going forward"], correct:0, explanation:"Embedding appetite in performance discourages reckless pursuit of goals. It does not disregard risk, replace performance targets, or hand performance management to the risk team." },
  { id:40290, domain:1, level:2, question:"Which statement BEST describes the purpose of risk-related policies?", options:["To document the precise voltage requirements of equipment in the data center facility by design","To set expectations and direction for how risk should be managed across the enterprise","To record the personal vacation plans of each member of the executive leadership","To list the social media handles used by the organization for its public outreach"], correct:1, explanation:"Risk-related policies set expectations and direction for managing risk. They are not voltage specs, vacation plans, or social media handle lists." },
  { id:40291, domain:1, level:3, question:"A company wants assurance that controls remain effective as the business changes. Which governance practice supports this BEST?", options:["A single control assessment performed at deployment and never repeated afterward at all","Assuming controls remain effective indefinitely because they worked at the time of design by design","Periodic review of controls against evolving risks, objectives, and the changing environment","Delegating all control effectiveness judgments to the vendors who supplied the controls"], correct:2, explanation:"Periodic review keeps controls aligned with change. A one-time assessment, assuming permanence, or vendor self-judgment all fail to assure ongoing effectiveness." },
  { id:40292, domain:1, level:3, question:"How does risk governance promote accountability for risk decisions?", options:["By keeping decision-makers anonymous so that no one can be questioned afterward","By making all decisions collectively so no single party is ever truly accountable","By delegating every risk decision to external consultants who bear no consequences by design","By assigning clear owners and recording who decided, so decisions can be traced later"], correct:3, explanation:"Clear owners and recorded decisions enable traceability and accountability. Anonymity, diffuse collective decisions, or external delegation all weaken accountability." },
  { id:40293, domain:1, level:3, question:"What is the purpose of aligning compliance requirements with the risk register?", options:["To ensure regulatory obligations are tracked, prioritized, and managed alongside other risks","To remove compliance obligations from oversight once they appear in any document","To treat compliance as wholly separate so it never informs risk prioritization in any way at any time","To guarantee that the organization will never be subject to a regulatory penalty"], correct:0, explanation:"Aligning compliance with the register tracks and prioritizes obligations alongside other risks. It does not remove oversight, separate compliance, or guarantee no penalties." },
  { id:40294, domain:1, level:1, question:"Which of the following is a core principle of sound risk governance?", options:["Complete avoidance of every risk so the enterprise never accepts any exposure","Clear accountability for risk decisions held by parties with appropriate authority","Concentration of all decision authority within one individual for maximum speed","Treating risk management as a one-time exercise completed only at company founding"], correct:1, explanation:"Clear accountability held by appropriately authorized parties is a core principle. Total avoidance, single-person concentration, or one-time treatment all violate sound governance." },
  { id:40295, domain:1, level:2, question:"An enterprise's leaders make risk decisions inconsistent with the approved appetite. What governance weakness does this reveal?", options:["An appetite statement that is too detailed for leaders to ever read or understand","An excess of board oversight that prevents leaders from making any decisions in any way at any time","Inadequate enforcement and oversight of the appetite that leaders are expected to follow","A risk register so small that leaders have nothing meaningful left to decide upon"], correct:2, explanation:"Inconsistent decisions reveal weak appetite enforcement and oversight. It is not an overly detailed statement, excessive oversight, or an undersized register." },
  { id:40296, domain:1, level:2, question:"Why should risk governance ensure roles are understood, not just documented?", options:["Documentation alone always changes behavior, so understanding adds no further value by design","Roles need not be understood as long as a written record of them exists somewhere","Understanding roles is the sole responsibility of the external auditor each year","Understanding drives the behavior that documentation alone cannot produce in practice"], correct:3, explanation:"Understanding drives behavior that documentation alone cannot. Documentation does not automatically change behavior, understanding does matter, and it is not solely the auditor's job." },
  { id:40297, domain:1, level:3, question:"What is the benefit of senior management championing risk awareness initiatives?", options:["Visible leadership support increases engagement and embeds risk awareness across staff","Championing initiatives guarantees that no employee will ever ignore a risk again","Leadership support removes the need to allocate any budget to awareness activities by design","Championing confines risk awareness solely to the senior management team itself"], correct:0, explanation:"Visible leadership support boosts engagement and embeds awareness. It does not guarantee no one ignores risk, remove budget needs, or confine awareness to management." },
  { id:40298, domain:1, level:2, question:"Which of the following BEST describes the goal of risk governance?", options:["To create the maximum possible number of policies regardless of their usefulness","To direct, oversee, and embed risk management so it supports enterprise objectives","To ensure the risk team operates in isolation from the rest of the business units","To eliminate the need for any decisions by removing all uncertainty from operations"], correct:1, explanation:"Risk governance directs, oversees, and embeds risk management supporting objectives. It is not about maximizing policies, isolating the risk team, or removing all uncertainty." },
  { id:40299, domain:1, level:2, question:"A company wants its risk governance to remain effective through leadership turnover. Which approach BEST ensures continuity?", options:["Relying on the personal knowledge of a single long-tenured executive to hold it together","Rebuilding the entire governance framework from scratch each time a leader departs","Documenting roles, frameworks, and appetite so governance persists beyond any individual","Pausing all risk governance activity until new leadership is fully settled into the role"], correct:2, explanation:"Documented roles, frameworks, and appetite ensure governance persists beyond individuals. Relying on one person, rebuilding each time, or pausing all activity all jeopardize continuity." },
  { id:40300, domain:1, level:3, question:"How does effective risk governance ultimately create value for the enterprise?", options:["By avoiding every possible risk so that the enterprise never experiences any loss","By focusing solely on compliance paperwork without influencing any real decisions","By transferring all enterprise risk to third parties so leadership need not engage by design","By enabling informed risk-taking that supports objectives while protecting key assets"], correct:3, explanation:"Governance creates value by enabling informed risk-taking that supports objectives and protects assets. Total avoidance, paperwork-only focus, or blanket transfer do not create value." },
];
